, England":"Irchester, Northamptonshire, Engeland, Verenigd Koninkrijk","Walgrave, Northamptonshire, England":"Walgrave, Northamptonshire, England"},"en":{"1442–1487":"1442–1487","1444–1475":"1444–1475","1473–1485":"1473–1485","1470–Male":"1470–Deceased","1485–1516":"1485–1516","1422–1485":"1422–1485","1422–1486":"1422–1486","about 1470":"about 1470","1473":"1473","1470":"1470","1455":"1455","1422":"1422","1444":"1444","1487":"1487","1442":"1442","1486":"1486","1475":"1475","1485":"1485","29 April 1485":"29 April 1485","1516":"1516","Bentley, Hampshire, England":"Bentley, Hampshire, England","Bentley, Northamptonshire, England":"Northamptonshire, England","England":"England","Irchester, Northamptonshire, England":"Irchester, Northamptonshire, England, United Kingdom","Walgrave, Northamptonshire, England":"Walgrave, Northamptonshire, England","nameMeanings":[{"name":"Freeman","type":"LAST","attribution":"Dictionary of American Family Names © Patrick Hanks 2003, 2006.","meanings":["English: from Middle English <i>freman</i>, <i>fremon</i> ‘freeman, free-born man’ (Old English <i>frēomann</i>, <i>frīgmann</i>), used also occasionally as a personal name. As an African American surname it was in many cases adopted as a name denoting a man freed of slavery. See also   Fryman   and   Free  .","Irish: Anglicized (‘translated’) form of Gaelic <b>Ó Saoraidhe</b> (see   Seery  ).","Americanized form of French <b>Lafrenière</b> (see   Lafreniere  )."],"variants":[{"name":"Freemon","meanings":["Variant of   Freeman  ."]},{"name":"Free","meanings":["English: nickname or status name from Middle English <i>fre</i> ‘free’ (Old English <i>frēo</i>), with reference to either tenurial status (‘free born’) or to character (‘noble, generous, open-handed’).","Irish: variant of   Freeman  .","Americanized form of Swiss German and German   Frei   and   Frey  ."]},{"name":"Fryman","meanings":["Americanized form of Swiss German <b>Frymann</b> or German <b>Freimann</b> (see   Freiman  ), and possibly also of the Dutch cognate <b>Vrijman</b>.","English: from Middle English <i>friman</i> ‘free-born man’ (Old English <i>frīomann</i>, <i>frīgmann</i>), symonymous with   Freeman   1."]}]},{"name":"John","type":"FIRST","attribution":"Dictionary of First Names © Patrick Hanks and Flavia Hodges 1990, 2003, 2006.","meanings":["form of   John  , also used quite frequently in the English-speaking world. In Northern Ireland it is sometimes found as a variant of   Ewan ."],"variants":[]}],"historicEvents":[{"id":1705197,"age":13,"year":"1455","julianDay":2252488,"title":"Wars of the Roses","description":"Wars of the Roses was a series of English civil wars for control of the throne of England between the royal families House of Lancaster and the House of York. The name of the war was derived as the red rose was the symbol of the Lancastrians and the white rose was the symbol of the Yorks.","url":"https://www.history.com/topics/british-history/wars-of-the-roses","urlTitle":"History - Wars of the Roses","jurisdictionLevel":2}],"lifeSummary":"When John Freeman was born in 1442, in Northamptonshire, England, his father, Henry Freeman, was 20 and his mother, Joan Rudd, was 20. He married Dorothy Isham in 1473, in England. They were the parents of at least 2 sons. He died in 1487, in Bentley, Hampshire, England, at the age of 45, and was buried in England."},"et":{"1442–1487":"1442–1487","1444–1475":"1444–1475","1473–1485":"1473–1485","1470–Male":"1470–Surnud","1485–1516":"1485–1516","1422–1485":"1422–1485","1422–1486":"1422–1486","about 1470":"umbes 1470","1473":"1473","1470":"1470","1455":"1455","1422":"1422","1444":"1444","1487":"1487","1442":"1442","1486":"1486","1475":"1475","1485":"1485","29 April 1485":"29. aprill 1485","1516":"1516","Bentley, Hampshire, England":"Bentley, Hampshire, England","Bentley, Northamptonshire, England":"Northamptonshire, England","England":"England","Irchester, Northamptonshire, England":"Irchester, Northamptonshire, Inglismaa, United King